{"id":"1807.07445","submitter":"Sirui Lu","authors":"Tao Xin, Sirui Lu, Ningping Cao, Galit Anikeeva, Dawei Lu, Jun Li,\n  Guilu Long, and Bei Zeng","title":"Local-measurement-based quantum state tomography via neural networks","comments":"10 pages, 4 figures, 3 tables","journal-ref":"npj Quantum Inf 5, 109 (2019)","doi":"10.1038/s41534-019-0222-3","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Quantum state tomography is a daunting challenge of experimental quantum\ncomputing even in moderate system size. One way to boost the efficiency of\nstate tomography is via local measurements on reduced density matrices, but the\nreconstruction of the full state thereafter is hard. Here, we present a machine\nlearning method to recover the full quantum state from its local information,\nwhere a fully-connected neural network is built to fulfill the task with up to\nseven qubits. In particular, we test the neural network model with a practical\ndataset, that in a 4-qubit nuclear magnetic resonance system our method yields\nglobal states via the 2-local information with high accuracy. Our work paves\nthe way towards scalable state tomography in large quantum systems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 19 Jul 2018 14:01:57 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 11 Jan 2019 17:45:30 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-12-03"}
